GitLab recommends keeping sensitive values like tokens in the project’s Settings > CI/CD > Variables UI, while non-sensitive values can live in .gitlab-ci.yml. In the GitLab UI, the exact path is Project > Settings > CI/CD > Variables > Add variable. Protected variables are only available to pipelines running on protected branches or protected tags.

Step 1: Prepare Docker Hub

If nirajpal/demorepo does not already exist, create it in Docker Hub from My Hub > Repositories > Create repository. Docker Hub repo names must be unique and use lowercase letters, numbers, hyphens, or underscores. If you make it Public, anyone can pull it. If you make it Private, only you and collaborators can access it.

Create a Docker Hub personal access token from Docker Home > Account settings > Personal access tokens > Generate new token. Docker explicitly recommends PATs for CI/CD automation instead of using your account password, and those tokens are what you should use with docker login

Step 2: Create or reuse a GitLab token for the deploy job

Project > Settings > Access tokens. Save the token value immediately, because GitLab only shows it once

Step 3: Add the GitLab CI/CD variables

Settings > CI/CD > Variables > Add variable
DOCKERHUB_USERNAME = nirajpal
DOCKERHUB_TOKEN = your Docker Hub PAT
GITLAB_USER = any non-empty value, for example gitlab-ci
GITLAB_TOKEN = your GitLab project access token

Step 5: If your Docker Hub repo is private, add a pull secret in Kubernetes

kubectl create secret docker-registry dockerhub-creds \
  --docker-server=https://index.docker.io/v1/ \
  --docker-username=nirajpal \
  --docker-password='<DOCKERHUB_PAT>' \
  -n python-pipeline
  
Step 2: Create a project runner in GitLab

Settings → CI/CD → Runners
Then:
Click Create project runner
Select Linux as the platform
Set the runner tag to: docker
Add a description like python-pipeline-docker-runner
Create the runner
Copy the runner authentication token that starts with glrt-  

This matters because all your jobs use:
tags:
  - docker
  
Step 3: Prepare a separate runner VM

sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y ca-certificates curl
sudo install -m 0755 -d /etc/apt/keyrings
sudo curl -fsSL https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu/gpg -o /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.asc
sudo chmod a+r /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.asc

echo \
  "deb [arch=$(dpkg --print-architecture) signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/docker.asc] https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu \
  $(. /etc/os-release && echo "${UBUNTU_CODENAME:-$VERSION_CODENAME}") stable" \
  | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list > /dev/null

sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y docker-ce docker-ce-cli containerd.io docker-buildx-plugin docker-compose-plugin
sudo docker run hello-world  

curl -L "https://packages.gitlab.com/install/repositories/runner/gitlab-runner/script.deb.sh" -o script.deb.sh
less script.deb.sh
sudo bash script.deb.sh
sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y gitlab-runner

